In particular, one really cool aspect of the nematocyst is completely ignored in the video, and so far as I can try to see (through all the bible thumpers, and then others taking their bait) it's also neglected in the comments.  It's too bad both guys who spoke in the video glossed over this:

The nematocyst does have a tube that injects poison, but it the way it punctures you is NOT the way a hypodermic does.  It doesn't stab -- it CHAINSAWS.  

The way the coiled tube extends is not just to stiffen – the way it extends is by turning inside out, like a shirt sleeve.  One end of the coiled tube is connected to the wall of the cyst, the way your clothes dryer duct is connected to the outside wall of your house; the other end of the coil is sitting loose inside the cyst, and is open-ended.

The nematocyst fires by a reaction that suddenly transports more water into the cyst, causing a pressure increase in the poisonous fluid inside.  This makes the tube begin to evert itself through the place where it's connected to the wall of the cyst.  As it does, the cyst pressure inflates the tube and extends it, drawing more of the tube out, through the inside of the part that's already extended, so that you have the inside tube feeding out through the middle of the extended part, extending the end by turning inside out at the tip.  

When the tube is sitting coiled up stored in the cyst, its inside surface is covered with tiny bristles.  As the tube extends when the cyst has fired, the bristles on the INSIDE of the tube emerge at the extending tip and flip around to sit on the OUTSIDE of the everted tube.  

By emerging around the bend in this motion, the bristles act as the teeth of a tubular chainsaw, ripping into anything they hit.  If it's your skin, they make a hole in it, and the tube goes on extending itself into the tissues under your skin.  Once it's fully extended, the pressurized fluid that's been driving all this – which is the poison – spills out the open end, into whatever cells the end has made its way to.

If the target is a big animal like we are, this acts as a defensive attack and after it's done its damage the tube breaks loose from the skin of the victim.  But if the target is a small creature attacked as prey, the tube (or probably a number of them fired at once) stay intact, like fishing lines hooked into the prey, and enable the jellyfish tentacle to haul the prey in so it can be eaten.
